{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R1\n    \n      Cinematic cold open · 15-second film on first visit\n      First URL load: fade from black. Soft piano. Text appears: \"Every system you've ever used...\" → \"...was built from 36 ideas.\" → \"Let's learn them.\" → fade to home screen. 15 seconds. Never again. Creates anchor memory of arrival.\n      \n        Every system you've ever usedwas built from 36 ideas.\n        ── LET'S LEARN THEM ──\n        skip intro","choice":"r1","id":null,"timestamp":1776681854956}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R2\n    \n      Spatial home · drafting table, not a dashboard\n      Home isn't widgets. Home is an isometric studio view. Your current work is on the drafting table (large central piece). Pattern shelves on the wall. Notebook (notes) on the side. Door to examination room (drill) in the corner. Everything has place.\n      \n        \n        \n          \n          \n          \n          \n          \n          \n          \n          \n        \n        ── PATTERN LIBRARY · 36 SHELVED ──\n\n        \n        \n          ── CURRENT BLUEPRINT ──\n          \n            \n            \n          \n          Observer · last edited 12 min ago\n        \n\n        \n        \n          notebook\n          \n        \n\n        \n        \n          🚪\n          EXAM\n          3 due\n        \n\n        \n        ☕\n      \n      Click shelves → library · click blueprint → Build · click notebook → notes · click door → Drill","choice":"r2","id":null,"timestamp":1776681872545}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R3\n    \n      Patterns as rooms · you walk into a pattern\n      Click Observer → screen transition = a door opens, you step into Observer's room. Walls = the UML diagram (depth/perspective). Floor = the code scroll. Ceiling = metadata (real-world uses, history). Door on wall leads to confused-with patterns (Pub-Sub across the hall). Navigation is architectural.\n      \n        \n        ─── REAL-WORLD USES · NETFLIX · REACT · NODE EVENTS ───\n        \n        \n          \n            Subject\n            →\n            \n              Obs1\n              Obs2\n            \n          \n        \n        \n        class Subject { notify() { subs.forEach(...) } }\n        \n        \n          🚪\n          PUB-SUB\n        \n      \n      Transition between patterns = camera \"walks through door\" · spatial memory = better recall","choice":"r3","id":null,"timestamp":1776685734442}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R4\n    \n      Radial command interface · press-hold anywhere, radial menu blooms\n      Figma-style. Long-press anywhere on canvas → radial menu appears around cursor with 6-8 context actions. Drag cursor to an arc, release to execute. No toolbars. No menus. Action is where your cursor is.\n      \n        \n        \n          \n          \n          \n          ＋ Class\n          ↔ Edge\n          ✂ Group\n          📝 Note\n          🤖 Ask AI\n          ⇨ Align\n        \n        Press-and-hold 200ms anywhere on canvas · menu blooms · drag to item · release.","choice":"r4","id":null,"timestamp":1776685744056}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R5\n    \n      Typography as architecture · editorial, not utility\n      Current LLD uses utility typography (Geist Sans, small sizes, flat). Rebuild: introduce a serif for long-form lesson content (New York Times essay feel) + monospace for code + the existing Geist for UI chrome. Three voices, three altitudes.\n      \n        The Observer's Dilemma\n        On loose coupling, and the price it exacts.\n        \n          Every system of substance comes, eventually, to the same problem. Something happened. Many things want to know. The question is never whether they should know, but how.\n        \n      \n      Lesson content styled like a printed magazine · feels like reading The Atlantic, not a wiki","choice":"r5","id":null,"timestamp":1776685751873}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R6\n    \n      Gesture grammar · pinch, two-finger rotate, swipe between patterns\n      Designed-for-trackpad-first interactions: pinch to zoom (natural), two-finger-rotate to reorient canvas, three-finger-swipe to navigate patterns, pinch-to-close to exit mode. Your hands drive the experience, not menus.\n      \n        \n          \n            🤏\n            Pinch\n            zoom canvas\n          \n          \n            🔄\n            2-finger rotate\n            reorient view\n          \n          \n            👋\n            3-finger swipe\n            prev/next pattern\n          \n          \n            🤲\n            Pinch-out\n            zoom back to studio","choice":"r6","id":null,"timestamp":1776685757989}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R7\n    \n      Ambient soundscape + dynamic lighting · atmosphere per pattern\n      Each pattern category has a subtle ambient sound (optional, off by default): Creational = light rain + paper rustle. Behavioral = soft café hum. Resilience = low hum of server room. Plus dynamic ambient lighting — canvas background subtly shifts warm/cool with time of day. Makes the app feel inhabited.\n      \n        \n          \n            MORNING · 9:14 AM\n            Warm light · higher saturation · 🎵 soft jazz café\n          \n          \n            EVENING · 10:47 PM\n            Cool light · lower saturation · 🎵 distant rain + low hum","choice":"r7","id":null,"timestamp":1776685777815}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R8\n    \n      Fluid layout · no hard panels, everything overlaps and breathes\n      Apple's macOS design language evolved to fluid translucent panels with overlap. Move sidebar → canvas fluidly reshapes. Close properties → it dissolves, doesn't snap. Every transition is material. No hard dividers.\n      \n        \n        \n        \n      \n      Translucent layers overlap · backdrop-filter: blur · never hard-edged","choice":"r8","id":null,"timestamp":1776685782692}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R10\n    \n      Presentation mode native · share your diagram as a deck\n      Hit Present. Your diagram becomes a self-paced slideshow: slide 1 intro, slide 2 the problem, slide 3 reveal class A, slide 4 reveal class B with animation, slide 5 the full pattern, slide 6 the tradeoffs. All auto-generated from your diagram + lesson data. Use in interviews, team demos, docs.\n      \n        Title\n        Problem\n        ◎ Now\n        Class B\n        Full","choice":"r10","id":null,"timestamp":1776685852273}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R9\n    \n      Personal architect signature · your designs get your mark\n      Sign-up: draw a signature with trackpad/mouse once. Every saved diagram has YOUR signature in the bottom corner (like blueprints signed by architects). Shared diagrams display it. Ownership feels personal.\n      \n        \n          \n          \n          \n        \n        \n          A. Garg\n          Observer v3 · 2026-04-20","choice":"r9","id":null,"timestamp":1776685853230}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R11\n    \n      Code ⇄ UML always in sync · dual-view as primary\n      Main view is split 50/50: code on left, UML on right. Edit code → UML updates live. Drag a class → code regenerates. They're two views of the same object, never separate. Inspired by RStudio's code+plot duality.\n      \n        \n          class Singleton {\n            static #instance;\n            static getInstance() {\n              return this.#instance\n                ??= new Singleton();\n            }\n          }\n        \n        \n          \n            Singleton\n            \n            - #instance\n            \n            + getInstance()","choice":"r11","id":null,"timestamp":1776685855077}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"R12\n    \n      First-time ritual · you're not signing up, you're being welcomed\n      Not a form. 4 screens: (1) cinematic intro (R1) (2) \"Sign the guest book\" — draw your signature (3) \"Pick your first pattern to meet\" — 3 curated choices (4) welcome to your studio, door opens to home. Total time: 90 seconds. Feels like joining an atelier, not registering a SaaS.\n      \n        \n          \"Every systemyou've ever used...\"\n        \n        \n          SIGN HERE\n          ✎\n        \n        \n          CHOOSE ONE\n          \n            \n            \n            \n          \n        \n        \n          🚪\n          WELCOME IN","choice":"r12","id":null,"timestamp":1776685865607}
